From AIDS, non-communicable diseases in eight fundamental points
GENEVA - Non-communicable diseases (NCDs), such as heart diseases, strokes, cancer, diabetes and chronic pulmonary diseases are responsible for 70% of all deaths.
There is irrefutable evidence that tobacco use, sedentary lifestyle, poor diet and excessive alcohol consumption increase the chances of dying prematurely from non-communicable diseases.
Yet despite widespread knowledge of the risks, global obesity is generally not controlled, while tobacco and alcohol consumption continue to rise.
It is in this context that the networks of alliances for non-communicable diseases met from December 9 to 11 at the second World Forum of the Alliance on Non-Communicable Diseases in the United Arab Emirates.
In their search for solutions aimed at regulating NCDs, they should draw inspiration from the HIV/AIDS fight movement.
People living with and affected by HIV continue to carry out interventions and their unique form of mobilization has been essential in the progress made.
Although the battle is not over, AIDS activists know that they can win this battle.
Similarly, a mobilization movement against NCDs can turn back this epidemic.
Yet in 2015, Richard Horton, editor-in-chief of The Lancet journal, described the NCD community as being in need of an "electric shock to its semi-comatose mind." He added: "But who will have the courage to administer it?"
We believe there are lessons to be learned from AIDS activists.
As global attention focuses on the prevention of NCDs, those seeking to control preventable diseases should draw inspiration from the ABC of AIDS fight organizations.
The first letter that the NCD community must consider is « A », as in activism.
Anyone over 40 surely remembers the images of AIDS activists participating in « die-ins » during scientific meetings around the world.
In the United States, AIDS activists went into the streets and even shut down the headquarters of the Food and Drug Administration for a day in October 1988.
On a a global scale, activists have pressured governments and pharmaceutical companies to make medicines more affordable.
This activism continues and should serve as a model for action on non-communicable diseases.
Next, the NCD community must adopt a bolder approach to budgets - the « B » of the AIDS fight movement's strategy.
Civic organization and grassroots activism can mobilize the initial energies, but organizing and maintaining a broad coalition needs money.
The AIDS fight movement was clear on this point from the beginning and pushed to obtain resources to effectively support its awareness and empowerment activities.
« C » represents coalitions: the movements fighting AIDS quickly realized that progress comes only with multiple supports.
Activists established links between people living with HIV and those with other concerns, such as women's rights, intellectual property rights, nutrition, and housing.
Coalitions and specialized campaigns work better when they bring together internal and external leaders from public authorities in order to combine their viewpoints and expertise.
The AIDS fight movement also realized that a comprehensive response to the epidemic is essential to the spread of its support.
Thus, « D », the determining factor of success, consisted of 'drawing attention to the interconnectivity of the challenge.
For example, lobbying education leaders to keep girls in school longer has contributed to providing young people with the knowledge and power to make intelligent decisions about when and with whom to negotiate protected sexual relationships.
Similarly, links have been established between groups working on poverty, gender equality, and nutrition: all factors that played a driving role in the AIDS crisis.
NCDs are no less isolated in their causality and are also subject to a multisectoral approach to prevention.
Commitment - « E » - has been what helped the AIDS movement gain such great influence.
By strategically borrowing from the disability rights movement, which championed the key phrase « Nothing about us without us », AIDS advocates demanded the representation of existing organizations to address the disease.
For example, UNAIDS remains the only United Nations agency with seats on its Board of Directors reserved for representatives of civil society.
This standard is so deeply embedded in the AIDS fight movement that it would almost be unthinkable for an AIDS-related meeting to take place without community representation.
Disease prevention movements must also develop convincing narratives and « F » - framing the issue - is essential for the AIDS community to gain political leaders' support.
In particular, access to AIDS treatments has been framed as an issue of economic justice.
Presenting the narrative in this way has led to a significant reduction in drug prices, to the extent that more than half of people living with HIV in low- and middle-income countries are on treatment.
An equally important formulation of the issue for AIDS, a very relevant question for the NCD movement, is that of responsibility.
The AIDS community has worked hard to focus more on people's lifestyle choices, rather than attributing responsibility to the state in the provision of healthcare and in the elimination of legal discrimination.
In the AIDS debate, gender - the « G » of our movement - has been a significant point.
HIV was initially considered a « disease of gays » and gender identity has been rooted in the DNA of the AIDS fight movement from the beginning.
The gender dimensions of these diseases are no less important: it is enough to examine the way in which alcohol and tobacco are marketed to understand this.
Gender, therefore, must become a focus of efforts to prevent NCDs.
Finally, « H » - human rights - are the foundation of the response to AIDS.
Campaigns have been launched against discrimination in the workplace, in schools, and in medical centers.
The strategic litigation has ensured equality under the law.
The AIDS fight movement refused to hold major conferences in countries with repressive laws against people living with HIV.
The NCD movement could adopt the same tactic, for example, by refusing to meet in countries that fail to limit the advertising of unhealthy foods to children.
We could continue through the alphabet the list of lessons learned from the fight against AIDS, but we think it is appropriate to close it on « H », given that human rights have provided the answer to AIDS and they should provide the answer to non-communicable diseases.
Poverty, exclusion, as well as social and economic marginalization put people at greater risk of HIV.
The same is true for NCDs.
The first reaction to the AIDS epidemic was to ask: « Why don't these people make better choices? » The AIDS fight movement clearly stated that this question is not the right one.
Today, with 70% of the planet at risk of premature death due to preventable diseases, « these people » represent a large number of us.
The NCD and AIDS communities can learn from one another.
We are a stronger movement when we unite our forces.
The opinions expressed here do not necessarily reflect those of UNAIDS.
